library(cluster)
library(dendextend)
library(factoextra)
library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(broom)
customer_data <- read_csv("data/mall_customers.csv") %>% 
  clean_names() %>% 
  column_to_rownames("customer_id") %>% 
  rename(annual_income = annual_income_k,
         spending_score = spending_score_1_100)

customer_data %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = age, y = annual_income, colour = gender) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  facet_grid(~ gender)

Comment: For females, looks like there are groupings - between ages 25-40 with annual income between 50k and 75k - between 20 and 35 with annual income less than 50k For males, looks like there are groupings - between 20 and 40 with low annual income - between 25 and 50 with annual income c75k

customer_data %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = annual_income, y = spending_score, colour = gender) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  facet_grid(~ gender)

Comment: For females, looks like there are five groupings radiating out from a central group where nnual_income c50k and spending score c50 Other four groups then become low income/low score, low income/high score, high income/low score, high income/high score

Similar pattern for males although perhaps not as distinct for the lower income groups

customer_data %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = age, y = spending_score, colour = gender) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  facet_grid(~ gender)

Comment: For both females and males looks like there is a grouping of under 40s with high spending score

customer_income_spend <- customer_data %>% 
  select(annual_income, spending_score)
fviz_nbclust(customer_income_spend, 
             kmeans, 
             method = "wss", 
             nstart = 25)

  print.data.table

Looks like the "elbow’ occurs at k = 5

fviz_nbclust(customer_income_spend, 
             kmeans, 
             method = "silhouette", 
             nstart = 25)

Again, maximum occurs at k = 5

             kmeans, 
             method = "gap_stat", 
             nstart = 25, 
             k.max = 10)

.................................................. 50

Again, looks like optimal number of clusters is 5

clusters <- kmeans(customer_income_spend, centers = 5, nstart = 25)
clustered_customer <- augment(clusters, customer_data)
clustered_customer %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = annual_income, y = spending_score, colour = .cluster) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(title = "Clustered customer data",
       x = "Annual income (k)",
       y = "Spending score",
       colour = "Cluster")

The clustering seems to be a good fit for this data and confirms the comments made in the initial data exploration.

The clusters could be described as:

  1. Higher income / higher spending score
  • Incomes above 75k and spending scores of c60 and above. This cluster is quite spread out along the income axis, with no upper bound on income.
  1. Lower income / lower spending
  • Incomes of c40k and below, with spending scores of c45 and below. This cluster is tightly spread along the income axis, as there is a lower bound (0) on income
  1. Middle income/middle spend
  • This cluster is tightly packed around the 50k income and 50 spending score region.
